properties.Name: North East
properties.Impact: Increased personal allowances will lift 34,000 people out of income tax and benefit over 940,000, Newcastle will become a “super-connected city”, receiving funding of up to £6 million, Local Enterprise Partnerships will get additional funding of over £10m from the Growing Places Fund

properties.Name: North West
properties.Impact: Increased personal allowances will lift 95,000 people out of income tax and benefit over 2.5 million, the Government will support Network Rail to invest a further £130 million in the Northern Hub rail scheme, Local Enterprise Partnerships will get additional funding of over £31 million from the Growing Places Fund

properties.Name: London
properties.Impact: Increased personal allowances will lift 97,000 people out of income tax and benefit over 3 million, 100 per cent capital allowances for plant or machinery investment will be available in a designated area of the London Royal Docks Enterprise Zone, the Greater London Authority will get an allocation of £70 million from the Growing Places Fund

properties.Name: West Midlands
properties.Impact: Increased personal allowances will lift 74,000 people in the West Midlands out of income tax and benefit over 1.9m individuals, Birmingham will become a “super-connected city”, receiving funding of up to £10 million, Local Enterprise Partnerships will receive additional funding of over £74m from the Growing Places Fund

properties.Name: Yorkshire and The Humber
properties.Impact: Increased personal allowances will lift 74,000 people out of income tax and benefit over 1.8m individuals, the Government will support Network Rail to invest a further £130m in the Northern Hub rail scheme, serving stations in West Yorkshire, Local Enterprise Partnerships in Yorkshire and Humber will receive additional funding of over £71million from the Growing Places Fund

properties.Name: South West
properties.Impact: Increased personal allowances will lift 73,000 people out of income tax and benefit over 2 million individuals, Local Enterprise Partnerships will get additional funding of over £23 million from the Growing Places Fund, the establishment of two Rural Growth Network pilots in the Heart of the Southwest Local Enterprise Partnership (which covers Devon and Somerset and the Swindon and Wiltshire LEP)

properties.Name: East Midlands
properties.Impact: Increased personal allowances will lift 66,000 people out of income tax and benefit over 1.7 million, current Right To Buy regional discount cash caps will be replaced by a cap of £75,000 (worth more than three times the current East Midlands cap of £24,000) Local Enterprise Partnerships will get additional funding of over £24 million from the Growing Places Fund

properties.Name: South East
properties.Impact: Increased personal allowances will lift 104,000 people out of income tax and benefit over 3.3 million individuals, a Government commitment to work with Network Rail, train operators, TfL and the Mayor to improve national rail journeys into London, £56 million of support for the Bexhill to Hastings link road, Local Enterprise Partnerships will get additional funding of over £46 million from the Growing Places Fund

properties.Name: East of England
properties.Impact: Increased personal allowances will lift 75,000 people out of income tax and benefit around 2.2 million, the Government has identified a shortlist of options to improve road capacity on the A14 between Huntingdon and Cambridge, Local Enterprise Partnerships will get additional funding of over £16 million from the Growing Places Fund

properties.Name: Scotland
properties.Impact: Increased personal allowances will lift 73,000 people out of income tax and benefit 2.1 million individuals, 100 per cent capital allowances being made available to support investment at designated sites in Irvine, Nigg and Dundee (potential to deliver more than 4,000 new jobs), oil and gas measures to secure billions of pounds of additional investment in the UK Continental Shelf, corporation tax reliefs for the video games industry (will help support investment in development hubs at Dundee and Edinburgh), up to £11 million of investment in Edinburgh to deliver ultra-fast broadband to up to 180,000 residents and 8,000 businesses, investment in mobile infrastructure to deliver improved coverage, £20.3 million of Barnett consequentials (taking the amount of additional funding provided to Scotland since the Spending Review to more than £1 billion)

properties.Name: Wales
properties.Impact: Increased personal allowances will lift 42,000 people out of income tax and benefit 1.1 million individuals, 100 per cent capital allowances being made available to support investment at designated sites in Deeside, North Wales (potential to deliver more than 5,000 new jobs), commitment to electrification of the Cardiff valley rail lines, up to £12 million of investment in Cardiff to deliver ultra-fast broadband to up to 142,000 residents and 10,000 businesses, investment in mobile infrastructure to deliver improved coverage, £11.7 million of Barnett consequentials (taking the amount of additional funding provided to Wales since the Spending Review to nearly £500 million)

properties.Name: Northern Ireland
properties.Impact: Increased personal allowances will lift 25,000 people out of income tax and benefit 605,000, up to £13.7 million of investment in Belfast to deliver ultra-fast broadband to up to 113,000 residents and 9,000 businesses, investment in mobile infrastructure to deliver improved coverage, a delay in the planned increase in the aggregates levy rate which will avoid placing further burdens on the Northern Ireland quarrying industry, £14.3 million of Barnett consequentials (taking the amount of additional funding provided to Northern Ireland since the Spending Review to more than £450 million)
